### TITLE ###
No truncation when table fits
### DESCRIPTION ###
Table easily fits in terminal width - no truncation should occur.
### INPUT ###
Name = ["Alice", "Bob"]
Age = [30, 40]
rad:
    fields Name, Age
### TERM_WIDTH ###
80
### STDOUT ###
Name   Age 
Alice  30   
Bob    40   

### TITLE ###
One wide column truncated
### DESCRIPTION ###
One column is much wider than others, should be proportionally reduced.
### INPUT ###
Id = [1, 2]
Description = ["A very long description that exceeds terminal", "Another lengthy description for testing here"]
rad:
    fields Id, Description
### TERM_WIDTH ###
35
### STDOUT ###
Id  Description                  
1   A very long description tha…  
2   Another lengthy description…  

### TITLE ###
All columns wide - proportional reduction
### DESCRIPTION ###
All three columns exceed their entitlement (termWidth/numCols = 10) by
different amounts (1, 2, 3), so the reduction is distributed proportionally.
Exercises the primary overspill branch with multiple participating columns.
### INPUT ###
First = ["Alessandria", "Constantine"]
Second = ["Philadelphia", "Pennsylvania"]
Third = ["Massachusetts", "Revolutionary"]
rad:
    fields First, Second, Third
### TERM_WIDTH ###
30
### STDOUT ###
First      Second    Third   
Alessand…  Philade…  Massac…  
Constant…  Pennsyl…  Revolu…  

### TITLE ###
Narrow terminal - reduction below minimum leaves column untruncated
### DESCRIPTION ###
Edge case: when proportional reduction would drive a column's width to 1 or
lower, truncateString leaves the content unchanged (since there's not enough
room even for an ellipsis). The table then overflows the terminal width.
Documents current behavior; if we ever add a minimum floor to reduceColWidths
this test should be updated.

With termWidth=15 and cols [Name=5, Age=3, City=8], entitlement=5, City
exceeds by 3 and absorbs all 8 chars of reduction, leaving City at width 0.
### INPUT ###
Name = ["Alice", "Bob"]
Age = [30, 40]
City = ["New York", "LA"]
rad:
    fields Name, Age, City
### TERM_WIDTH ###
15
### STDOUT ###
Name   Age  City     
Alice  30   New York  
Bob    40   LA        

### TITLE ###
Wide column with narrow columns
### DESCRIPTION ###
Narrow columns should be minimally affected; wide column absorbs most reduction.
### INPUT ###
Id = [1, 2]
X = ["a", "b"]
Description = ["This is a really long description field value", "Another verbose description text right here ok"]
rad:
    fields Id, X, Description
### TERM_WIDTH ###
40
### STDOUT ###
Id  X  Description                    
1   a  This is a really long descrip…  
2   b  Another verbose description t…  

### TITLE ###
Even distribution no column exceeds entitlement
### DESCRIPTION ###
All columns are within entitlement but padding overhead causes overflow.
Exercises the else branch in reduceColWidths.
### INPUT ###
AA = ["abcd", "efgh"]
BB = ["ijkl", "mnop"]
CC = ["qrst", "uvwx"]
DD = ["yzab", "cdef"]
rad:
    fields AA, BB, CC, DD
### TERM_WIDTH ###
22
### STDOUT ###
AA   BB   CC   DD   
ab…  ij…  qr…  yzab  
ef…  mn…  uv…  cdef  

### TITLE ###
Transposed table no truncation
### DESCRIPTION ###
Transposed table fits in terminal width.
### INPUT ###
Name = ["Alice", "Bob"]
Age = [30, 40]
rad:
    transpose
    fields Name, Age
### TERM_WIDTH ###
80
### STDOUT ###
Name  Alice  Bob  
Age   30     40   

### TITLE ###
Transposed table truncated
### DESCRIPTION ###
Transposed table truncation of values and potentially header names.
### INPUT ###
Name = ["Alexander Hamilton", "Elizabeth Montgomery"]
Age = [30, 40]
rad:
    transpose
    fields Name, Age
### TERM_WIDTH ###
30
### STDOUT ###
Name  Alexander…  Elizabeth…  
Age   30          40          

